title: St Dunstan-in-the-West
description:
The church of St Dunstan-in-the-West is in Fleet Street in London. A fragment of the old churchyard remains near Bream's Buildings.
First founded around 1000 AD, there is a possibility that a church on this site was one of the Lundenwic strand settlement churches, like St Martin's in the Fields, the first St Mary le Strand, St Clement Danes and St Brides. These may well pre-date any of the churches within the City walled area. It was first mentioned in 1185. Henry III gained possession of it and its endowments from Westminster Abbey by 1237 and then granted these and the advowson to the 'House of Converts' ie of the converted Jews, which led to its neglect of its parochial responsibilities. This institution was eventually transformed into the court of the Master of the Rolls.
St Dunstan is the only church in England to share its building with the Romanian Orthodox community.

http://www.stdunstaninthewest.org/

title: Brick Lane Great Mosque
description:
Brick Lane Jamme Masjid ("Brick Lane Great Mosque") formerly known as the London Jamme Masjid ("London Great Mosque") 
A Grade II* Listed Building
The Brick Lane Jamme Masjid Trust Ltd
59 Brick Lane, London, E1 6QL
020 7247 6052

Former site of:

• 1743 Originally La Neuve Eglise, a French Protestant Church Built by the Huguenots.
• 1819 Methodist Chapel (Wesleyan Chapel).
• 1898 Spitalfields Great Synagogue (Machzike Hadath).
• 1976 The Brick Lane Jamme Masjid.

“The building that houses the Jamme Masjid, as has often been remarked, represents the history of successive communities of immigrants into London; from this point of view it may be called one of the most remarkable and evocative buildings in the area and one of London’s architectural and historic treasures” 
Inwood 1998, 869 & Nairn 1966, 168.

Read more from the websites below:

title: St. Andrew-by-the-Wardrobe
description:
St. Andrew-by-the-Wardrobe is an Anglican church located on Queen Victoria Street, London in the City of London, near Blackfriars station.

First mentioned around 1170, the church was almost certainly founded considerably earlier; during the 13th century the church was a part of Baynard's Castle, an ancient royal residence. In 1361, Edward III moved his Royal Wardrobe (a storehouse for Royal accoutrements, housing arms and clothing among other personal items of the Crown) from the Tower of London to just north of the church. It was from this association that the church acquired its unique name. The Wardrobe and the church, however, were both lost in the Great Fire of London in 1666. Of the 51 churches designed by Sir Christopher Wren after the Fire, St. Andrew-by-the-Wardrobe is among the simplest of his designs, rebuilt in 1695 but again destroyed by German bombing in the Second World War, with only the tower and walls surviving. It was re-dedicated in 1961.

http://www.standrewbythewardrobe.net/

title: St Mary Aldermary
description:
Church of England. Rebuilt by Sir Christopher Wren. The design is said to be based on the pre-fire church, following a condition set down in the will of a benefactress. It is thus one of Wren's few buildings in what we now call the Gothic style. To Wren, this was the "modern" style, as opposed to the "ancient" or classical.
